Halfway through a 10-year program to save the Chesapeake Bay, political leaders are acknowledging that the vaunted cleanup is faltering and are calling for major changes midstream.
Once touted as a national model, the cleanup effort has unraveled into what some environmentalists call a bureaucratic farce.
Five years of planning, they say, have left the bay no cleaner than it was when the ``Chesapeake 2000'' pact was signed.
A Maryland congressman is contemplating legislation to replace the voluntary cleanup strategy with strict regulatory requirements.
Governors are pledging to walk the halls of Congress lobbying for $12 billion in needed support.
